TLANDT ST 9-11DEV S*\nFOREST HILLS INN\nFOREST HILLS GARDENS, L. I.\n}f minute? (actual running time) from\ni'emia Station. V. J. HAWLJBY. M*r.\nPrlvaie fsnUUea harto* a ?pare room\nto reni will And The Tribune'* ?T-urnlshed\nRoorne'-to Let column an aid to n.'iniag It.\n?Fiioaa BctScsxM. 1090.?Advt,\nof the Association of Railway Execu?\ntives, issued a statement here yester?\nday which defends his action in calling\nfor the abrogation of war-time wage\nagreements between the railroads and\nbrotherhoods and which sets forth that\nin January thirty-six of the roads, ac\ncording to their own figures, failed to\nearn operating expenses.\nIt is pointed out a? the results of\ncanvass made of January earnings that\ntwenty-eight other roads estimate\nthey did not earn enough above operat?\ning expenses to meet taxes and fixed\ncharges for this period.\n\"Under present traffic and operating\nconditions,\" General Attcrbury says,\n\"these were the results despite the fact\nthat the sixty-four companies referred\ni to have in the aggregate decreased\ni their labor cost operation by laying\noff approximately 200,000 employees\nsince September 1, 1920. These com?\npanies have a total main line mileage\nof more than 100,000 miles and con?\nstitute approximately 40 per cent of\nthe railroad mileage of the country.\n\"In addition there are other com?\npanies of well established earning\npower under normal conditions which\nexpect their earnings for January to\nexceed their fixed charges by only\nnarrow margin.\nLooks to Labor Board\n\"The railroads cannot believe thai\nthe Railway Labor Board, which, by its\nwage decision of July 22, 1920, has\nkept these national agreements, rules\nand working condition? in existenc?\nsince September 1, can or will deny\nto the railroads and to the public the\nrelief requested.\n\"Included in the figures of lay-offs\nand mileage are companies which J\nhave not specifically mentioned which ir\nprevious years, also have had difficult}\nin approximating a fair earning power\nIn a developing country like the United\nStates there always have been' suer\nrailways. Their economic and traffic\nconditions have not justified the pay?\nment of trunk line wages nor the ob\nservance of trunk line conditions oi\nwork, even when these have been iai\nmore reasonable and less costly thai\nat present. Nevertheless, the augmen\ntation of their difficulties only f.oei\nti illustrate that it is economically\nj unsound and can only be fraught witl\ndisaster to attempt to compel all th?\nrailroads of the country, regardless o\ntheir differing conditions, to meet ore\ncisely the same wages and workinj\nconditions.\"\nCharges Misrepresentation\nGeneral Atterbury says:\n'.'Our application to terminate im\nmediately the war-time working agree\nments is simply the attempt to secur\ngovernment sanction for the necessar\nprocess whereby these railroads ca\nagain fit their expenses and operatin\nrules to the conditions of the terr;\ntories whose public servants they ar?\nHe adds:\n\"All the suggestions for laying thi\nmatter before Congress or some othe\npublic body, with the implication thf\nthe condition is not really seriou;\nwill, I am sure, mislead no one.\"\n\"Hence,\" concludes the statement, \"i\naccordance with the letter and spir\nof the transportation act, the railroat\nare before the one body whfCh ougl\nto grant them relief, namely, th\nUnited States Railway Labor Boar\nThe fight which the railroads are no\nmaking is not only their own figh\nbut the fight ?f the farmer, of the coi\nsumer and of the working man ar\nemployer in every industry of tl\nj country.\"\nThe thirty-six roads which estim?t*\nthat they had failed to earn operatir\ni expenses in January, and which we\ncited by General Atterbury in his stat\nj ment, include, among others, the A\nlanta, Birmingham Atlantic, Buffa\nSusquehanna, Central of Georgi\nDetroit, Toledo Ironton, Erie, Gre\nNorthern, Gulf Ship Island, Hoc\ning Valiey, Maine Central. New Yoi\nNew Haven Hartford, Northern F\ncific and Philadelphia Reading.\nAmong the twenty-eight others c\nfered as examples of failure* to ea\ntaxes and fixed charges are Arizo\nEastern, Atlantic Coast Line. Baltimo\nOhio, Boston Maine, Chicago, 1\ndianapolis Louisville, Chicago, M\nwaukee St. Paul, Chicago, Re\nIsland Pacific, Lehigh Valley, Mini\napolis St. Louis, Missouri Paci:\nNorfork Southern, Pennsylvania Ra\nroad. P?re Marquette, Western Maj\nland and the Wheeling Lake Erie\n\nZion City Sisters Who Came\nTo Save New York Disappe\nAfter a two weeks' crusade in i\nmovement to deliver the sinful of N\nI York from the downward path, the t\neisfc-i'-s nom Zion City who aspired\nj that task have disappeared. Pack;\ni their Leaves of Healing, clothing\n?,trher possessions into a single \"tri\n?Wednesday afternoon, Miss Bt\nj Schelhorn and Miss Helen Buhman\nI parted from their rooming house\n148 East Forty-fifth Street, and fai\nto leave a forwarding address.\nA Double Benefit\nOur plan for subdividing the larger\nmortgages brings within the reach of all the\nopportunity to invest in one of^the s?test\nsecurities in the world?one on wliich there\nhas never been a loss to any investor?First\nMortgage Certificates. Just now they yield\na higher return than ever before, 5*/2%*\nBy putting your money into this form ?~>f\ninvestment you not only benefit yourself but,\nin addition, do something towards relieving\nthe housing shortage, because the more\nmoney invested in mortgages the more\nmoney available for new homes.\nBond Mortgage Guarantee Co.\n1 76 Broadway, New York City\n175 Remiten Street, Brooklyn\n370,000 to Quit,\nLeader Says, if\nRoads Cut Pay\n(?\"??nilmisd frot-i pas?! ene)\nbor Board chamber was filled with\n1 spectators to hear the employees' reph\nto the Atterbury request, but labor\nrepr?sentatives failed to appear at the\nlast minute, and at their request the\nboard granted them until Monday to\npresent their aid*\nAccording to the present program\nseveral statements will be presented to\nthe board when the fifth week of hear?\nings convenes Monday morning. R. M.\nJewell, representing railroad employees\nof the American Federation of Labor,\nwho will make the principal reply, has\nbeen in conference with labor leaders\nall week preparing hi3 answer.\nE. T. Whiter, chairman of the car?\nriers' committee, read a supplementary\nstatement from General Atterbury in\nthe nature of a reply to charges made\nbv Mr. Jewell in a telegram to the\nPresident, that the roads could not\nsupport their claims of threatened\nfinancial disaster. The statement also\nwas made public in New York.\nNo decision on General Atterbury's\nrequest for immediate abrogation tfj\nthe agreements will be rendered by the\nboard until after the employees make\ntheir reply next Monday. A speedy\nruling on the matter is expected fol-\nlowing the employees' appearance, j\nhowever.\nBrotherhood Chief s\nExplain Opposition\nCarter and Sheppard Tell Why\nThey Believe Wage Agree\nments Ought to Stay Intact\nThe opposition of labor leaders to\nthe request of the railroads for the\nabrogation of national wage agree?\nments was voiced in statements re?\nceived by wire by The Tribune last\nnight from the heads of two of the\nprincipal employees' organizations,\nwhose views had been asked. W. S.\nCarter, president of the Brotherhood\nof Locomotive Firemen and Engineers,\ntelegraphed from Cleveland:\n\"All of the wage increases received\nby railroad employees since 1910 have\nnot materially increased labor costs.\n1er 1,000-ton miles, in the compensa?\ntion of engineers and firemen. Neither\nthe railroads nor the public is paying\nmore to engineers and firemen per\nunit of product than in the past. Dur?\ning depressions in railroad business\nj the railroads have offset losses by im?\nmediately reducing engineers to fire\nj men's positions and laying off many\ni thousands of firemen. The transporta\nI tion act requires the Labor Board to\nIrroperiy and justly fix compensation\nof employees and directs the Interstate\nj Commerce Commission to establish\npassenger and freight rates. This has\nbeen done. After having secured\nenormous returns under the provisions\nof the act the railroads now propose\nto grasp all the benefits of the rate\nincreases by reducing the wages of\ntheir employees. The enormous sums\ndue by the railroads to the government\nbecause of oyermaintenence during\nFederal control will be offset by addi?\ntional claims against the government\nj for so-called damages during Federa!\nj control.\"\nL. E. Sheppard, president of the Order\nof Railway Conductors, telegraphed\nfiom Cedar Rapids, Iowa:\n\"Representatives of railroad owners\nhave appeared before the United States\n1 Railroad Labor Board and requested\nauthority to materially reduce wages.\n1 This action is inconsistent and unwar\nj ranted. Most railroad workers are\nI piece workers and are only used when\n100% American\nAt the close of a recent inter?\nview Mrs. Harding, wife of the\nPresident-elect, remarked, \"I am\n100 per cent American, and this\napplies to clothes as well as every?\nthing else.\" To such expressions?\nAll Hail! The country is safe\nwith these real Americans in the\nWhite House.\nSentiments of this kind appeal\nvividly to every patriotic American\ncitizen. They are in full accord\nwith that Americanism which we\nhave been priviledged to preach\nand to practice in our fifty years of\nbusiness life.\nThousands of Americans know\nof that practice through wearing\nCOWARD Shoes. They know\nthat every COWARD Shoe is\nmade with American materials\nthroughout;every item of labor and\ndistribution is of American origin;\ncontented American workmen are\npaid in good American dollars; fac?\ntories and equipment are supported\nby American capital.\nThey know this because Coward\nShoes have proven a real invest?\nment, dollar for dollar, in appear?\nance, in comfort, and in service.\nneeded. The railrc ds have been\ngranted substantial increases in rates.\nRepeated statements as to a material\nreduction in the cost of living are not\nmuch in evidence in the necessaries\nof life.\n\"The railroads after many years\nhave succeeded In coupling wages with\nrates for transportation, ignoring\nmany very essential and important fac?\ntors. The railroad are practically\nguaranteed certain profits. This is not\ndone by the government for any other\nemployer of labor. Transportation\nemployees who patriotically refused to I\nstrike during the war were the last to\nreceive any increase, and while not i\nthreatened at this time as to reduction I\nof compensation they may be asked to\naccept reductions if the present efforts\no? the railroad owners prove success?\nful. A few months in the reconstruc?\ntion period, after the World War, is\nnot typical of conditions and no change\nin railway employees' compensation\nshould be considered until after a fair\ntrial of at least one year.\"\nLandis Asked to Explain\nRight to Take Ball Job\nWASHINGTON. F?b. 3.-?Acceptance\nby Federal ?J-mdge tandis of the posi?\ntion of r.Tgh commissioner of baseball\nbrought additional action to-day from\nRepresentative Welty, of Ohio. Mr.\nWelty, who yesterday introduced in the\nHouse a resolution proposing a Con?\ngressional investigation of Judge Land\nis's acceptance, announced ht. Had\nacted as follows:\nRequested Judge Landis by letter to,\nstate by what authority he accepted the\"\nbaseball position at a salary of $12,500\na year while serving as Federal judge\nfor the northern Illinois district.\nAsked Judge Landis to send him a\ncopy of the contract which he signed\nwith organized baseball to act as its\nchief arbitrator.\nCalled on United Stetes District At?\ntorney Clyne at Chicago to supply him\nwith a copy of the indictments pending\nagainst former members of -he Chicago\nAmerican club.\nWrote Attorney General Palmer ask?\ning if there was any law making it a\nmisdemeanor for a Federal judge to\nhold another position from which he\nreceived financial remuneration while\nholding his seat on the bench.\nRepresentative Welty also announced\nI that should he be informed by the At\ntorney General that it could not be con-\nsidered a misdemeanor under the law\nfor a Federal judge to accept financial\ncompensation for work other than that\nincident to his judicial duties, he pro- j\nposed to introduce a bill covering such i\na contingency.\nSchwab Sails for\nRest and to Study\nBusiness Outlook\nWill Visit England, France\nand Italy to Seek Open?\nings for American Capital\nTo Look Into Armaments\nCharles M. Schwab, cTiatrman of the\nunited States Steel Corporation, sailed\nfor Europe.on the Cunard liner Aqui\ntania yesterday. He was accompanied\nby Dr. Samuel A. Brown, head of the\nBellcvue Medical College.\n\"I am going to Europe for two rea?\nsons,\" Mr. Schwab said yesterday. \"I\nam going first for recreation and rest.\nI am also planning to fitudy conditions\nin England, France and Italy?particu?\nlarly the last country. I expect to take\nparticular note of things in that coun?\ntry because my last visit there was\ntwenty years ago. I expect to study\nbusiness conditions at first hand and\nlearn as far as possible what oppor?\ntunities there are for American capital\nin Europe.\n\"In view of the fact that the question\nof disarmament is being so widely dis?\ncussed at this time, doubtless I shall\nhave something to say on that matter\nwhen I return. I shall be gone for only\nfive or six weeks, two months at the\nmost.\"\nMr. Schwab spoke gratefully of the\nsympathetic attitude which the public\nhad taken during the investigation of\nthe United States Shipping Board ac?\ntivities.\n\"I am a great believer in America\nand the American people,\" he said,\n\"and I feel we can solve all of our\nproblems, however difficult.\"\nOwing to the fact that the Aquitania\nsailed with the largest first class pas?\nsenger list taken out of this port on a\nmidwinter trip, the Marquis of Caris\nbrooke, the youngest son of the late\nPrince Henry of Battenberg and of\nPrincess Beatrice, one of the daughters\nof Queen Victoria, was fortunate in\nobtaining a small single ?stateroom on\nDeck C.\nThe Marquis, who has been the guest\nof General Cornelius Vanderbilt both\nhere and in Washington, seemed satis?\nfied with the arrangement. He is a\ndirector of the Lamport Holt steam?\nship line and expects to be engaged\nactively ?in shipping on his arrival in\nEngland.\nAmong others who sailed were Sir\nMortimer and Lady Davis, Countess\nEthel de Juhilhac, Countess Moroni,\nMr. and Mrs. Charles J. Housman,\nColonel A. Hamilton Gault? D. S, 0.;\nMr3. Charles De L. elrichs, General\nand Mrs. F. ,E. Meighan and Mr. and\nMrs. James De Rothschild.\n\nTyphus Found on Ship\nOne Victim and Two Suspect?ed\nCases Discovered at Hospital\nOne case of typhus and two sus?\npected victims were found yesterday\namong the steerage passengers of the\nsteamship Presidente Wilson, which ar?\nrived in Brooklyn Wednesday. Phy?\nsicians of the Long Island Hospital\nfound the typhus patient in a re\nexamination of a man sent there as a\npneumonia victim.\nThe quarantine flag was immediately\ni .-ed on the ship, and the commander\ngiven orders to anchor down the bay\ne three patients wiil be sent either\nto Swinburne or Hoffman island to?\nday. Other steerage passengers will\nbe sent to the. same place for examina?\ntion.\nLike The\nOld Songs\"\nAn evening by the fireside.\nJohn McCormack's golden voice singing '77s\nNot True.\nMelba singing Tosti's Good-Bye.\nWhitehill singing I Want to See the Old Home.\nAlma Gluck singing Home, Sweet Home, or Old\nBlack Joe.\nThere is a variety almost endless of the old\nheart songs, always ready for you to hear and\nenjoy, if you have\nAnd the Victor catalog of music, so large and all\ninclusive, brings the inspiration closer to everv\nhearth.\nYou may have YOUR Victrola immediately if\nyou wish it, on your own terms, within reasoh\nNOTICE TO VIOLINISTS\nWe now have some very fine French strings that\nwill be appreciated by all players of string instru\nments. s illsiru\nJOHN WANAMAKER\nVictrola Salons, Pint Gallery, New Building\nBroadway at Ninth, New York\nmmwmimmmm,\n1\n\n\nfes\nm\nw\ns\ns\ne\nH\n\n\n\n?S9\n9\njfranfeltn Simon\nA Store of Individual Shops\nFIFTH AVENUE, 37th ?nd 38th STS\nAnnouncing the Spring Vogue of\nImported English Tweed in\nMisses' Tailored Suits\n4500\nTweed assumes the sophistry of\nthe tailored suit, preserves the\ncoquetry of the youthful suit and\nsheds the pleasing charm of its\npresent like bits of springtime bor\ncolorings upon the immediate\nrowed from the months to come.\ne\n<Box <j?Codeis Introducing The fh(ew Straight J^ines In\n'Both ?oat and Skirt\nSpring Shades of B/ue9 l^ust, Lavender or Cray\nSizes 14 to 20 years\nOther Tweed Suits\n29,50 to 98,50\nMISSES' SUIT SHOP?Second Floor\nmMBmm&mmmmmmmMM%?m\\\n\nM\nm\n\nftanklin Simon Ca\nA Store of Individual Shops\nFIFTH AVENUE. 37th ?nd j8th STS.\nI\ns\n\na\n\n\n?3\n\nI\nI\ns\nS\nHerald the Dawn of a New Fashion in\nisses' Tailored Frocks\nd?fisses' Qoat ^Dresses\nof ?h?avy 'Blue Trico tine\n69.50\nTHE coat dress enters upon its spring\ncareer with its title to smartness\nalready established, for the Pans\ncouturiers of no less importance than\nLanvin, Cheruit and Jenny were its\nsponsors. In these models it has the\ndistinction becoming its dignity as\nYouths' first spring tailored frock.\nSpring Omature Introduces Latticed\nSi/? Braid, Silk and Time/\nSoutache Embroidery\nStzes 14 to 20 years\nOther Coat Dresses\n49.50 to 295.00\nMISSES' GOWN SHOP?Second Floor\nt^4\nw*\ni\nx*v\nI\n?1\n\nH","height":"25377","width":"20220"}}
